Republican strategy to prevent Obama's re-election
Republican leaders justified their policy for the need to fight against electoral fraud.
Now, the Brennan Center considers this latter a myth and claims that electoral fraud is less common in the United States than the number of people who die due to the fall of a lightning.
In fact, Republican lawyers have found no more than 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will in part undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike what happens in Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for the organization of federal elections in the United States.
And in that same line a majority of U.S. governments promulgated, from 2009, new laws that complicated the process of registration or voting.
This phenomenon has spread after the November 2010 elections that saw the rise of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, during the year 2011 180 bills were introduced that restricted the exercise of the right of vote in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present an identity document with a photo, in addition to a American citizenship proof.
On the other hand, those laws reduce the periods of anticipated vote, invalidate the right to register as an elector on the day of the scrutiny and withdraw their right to vote to citizens with criminal backgrounds.
Before the 2006 election, no U.S. state required the voters to present an identity document with photo.
The state of Indiana was the first to demand it.
The Supreme Court of the United States confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of the Indiana law.
Therefore, the Republican authorities have rushed to extend this practice to other states.
In recent years, these authorities have supported laws in 34 states to force voters to submit an identity document with photography.
It is important to keep in mind that, unlike what happens in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity document, such as the Social Security Card.
In fact, 11% of American citizens, i.e. 21 million people in voting age, do not have any identity documents with photographs issued by a government agency in their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack an identity document with those characteristics.
But, often, obtaining the required identity document costs more than a hundred dollars.
Thus, the new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and people with low income.
In fact, a 25% of African Americans, a 15% of people earning less than $35,000 a year, a 18% of citizens over the age of 65 and a 20% of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 don’t have an identity document with photography.
And there is more.
In many states students, the voters who vote most for Democratic candidates, cannot use the identity document with photo issued by their institution.
On the other hand, those same states authorize members of fishing or hunting clubs who usually vote for the Republican parties to use the documents issued by those clubs.
Before 2004 no state required the citizenship test to vote.
Arizona was the first state to present such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have adopted laws that require voters to demonstrate that they are American citizens.
These measures clearly seek to limit Hispanic voting.
Two out of three Spanish voters seem to support the Democratic Party.
On the other hand, Republican legislators supported in 2011 certain laws that abolished the registration of voters on the same day of the scrutiny in eight states.
In addition, they restricted the right of people and groups to create a service of help to the voters who would like to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general elections, voter registration campaigns contributed to the registration of about 10 million citizens.
The measures taken since 2009 have achieved that the registration rate of new voters fell in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators adopted laws in five other states that favoured the reduction of the voting period by advance.
For example, in the 2008 Florida elections, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African-Americans, while the latter represented only 13% of the state voters.
In the Spanish, exactly the same thing happened.
These represent only 11% of the voters, which is equivalent to 24% of the citizens who vote in advance.
However, the white, which represent 76% of the electorate, represent only 46% of the citizens who vote in advance.
Of course, the Democratic legislators and their supporters have strongly opposed the adoption of laws that restrict the registration of voters.
In this sense, the Democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The U.S. Fiscal Ministry has intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
The damage could be partially reduced.
For example, only 16 of 34 states adopted the law that required the submission of an identity document with photography.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the party character of the laws that have been voted, as it is clear that with them it is intended to influence the 2012 results in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report demonstrates that the states that have adopted such laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed in the electoral college to the presidency.
It is too early to assure if these legislative changes on the scale of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential elections.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, the measures will in part undermine the American democratic system.
