The Higgs Boson in detail
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson generated a great shock last summer, and with reason.
It is believed, in fact, that this boson is partition of the responsible mechanism of the mass of everything that exists in the universe, nothing more and nothing less.
And what’s more, it’s the particle whose existence was predicted by the standard model: our best or “less bad” explanation of the nature and behavior of the matter, which has not yet been observed empirically.
But for the physicists it is not completely clear that it is Higgs.
We know without a doubt that there is a new particle and that it looks very much like the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
Additionally, new data revealed this week at a major physics congress held in Kyoto seem to confirm that yes, although there are still no more data to be completely secure.
In any case, let’s assume that it’s about Higgs, as the chances of getting wrong seem to be few.
There is, in this great world, a widespread and inevitable law that implies that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to infringe that rule and do not try it too much, because it will end up becoming harmful.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been demonstrated that there is also a law of these characteristics: Pauli’s principle of exclusion, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same “quantum state”; a “state” which consists, grossly, of some of its characteristics.
Physicists classify the particles into two categories.
On the one hand, we meet the good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey the beginning of Pauli.
And on the other hand are the bosons, a dirty panda of anarchists that has no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means they can be found in the same place and at the same time.
According to the site The Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratories which, by the way, is extraordinary, the bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons, of which we will not talk here, and the "power particles", by which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would somehow be emparented.
These bosons, I could emphasize here, are not the exotic beasts we could believe.
In fact, if you can read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinaryly banal boson: the photon or the “light particle” that acts as the “messenger” of the electromagnetic force.
In fact, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it “desordins” the electromagnetic field in that precise environment; a little like when we throw a stone into a stain.
In this "disorder" a electromagnetic wave is born (from light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon; that is, one of the "power-bearing" bosons.
More stable field
The same happens with the Higgs boson, with the difference that it’s another field, the Higgs field, which needs to be “disordered” so that this boson appears.
Now, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field.To activate it, it is necessary to get to extremely high energies, a bit as if it was a ice pool in which only a thick rock could slide through the surface.
Therefore, an immense particle accelerator such as the CERN (the great hadron collisioner is a ring of 27 km of circumference!) is needed to reach such energy levels.
The analogue with the electromagnetic field is a new tool that explains the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles or all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like the magnets, do so, but others do not: a piece of paper, for example, will never be kept by itself stick to the door of a refrigerator.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do it have a mass, while the rest (as the photon, by the way), do not have it.
Now, what can all these investigations “contribute” to? asks Mrs. Plamondon.
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the standard model (MS), and also allows physicists to scrutine the differences between the observations and the predictions of the MS.
Many, on their part, want to be found, because the smallest difference could open a door to a “new physics” that taps certain hole in the model.
This, we have to say, has still enormous shortcomings, as it does not propose any explanation regarding gravity (ups!) or dark matter, which forms around 80% of the matter in the Universe (other ups!).
But we have not found such differences in the CERN so far.
Repercussions
The repercussions of such research on our day-to-day is difficult to predict, but we don’t think we’re wrong by saying that it won’t have any.
At the beginning of the 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the laboratories did not suspect at all the revolution their work would provoke.
They interviewed the scientific applications, but nothing more.
In fact, as physicist Willard Boyle said, who worked in the Bell laboratories, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who elaborated the first continuous laser (the first were pulsated) in 1962, at the beginning the laser was rather considered a "laboratory apparatus."
Imagine...
In addition, applications can also come from all the instruments that surround the research.
For example, the same Willard Boyle developed a light captor in 1969 in the course of his research in the field of optics.
Although it was not his original intention at all, this captor now serves as a "eye" for all digital devices in the world, which won him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
That doesn’t mean, of course, that the LHC activities necessarily want to transform our lives, but it’s never known...
