Bitcoin’s quota, after reaching the top of $30 (23 euros) in June 2011, fell to $2 five months later, before returning to round the $10 today (the quota is censored on the bitcoincharts.com page).
It’s nothing impressive if we compare it with global changes in real currency or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) was interested in him in a virtual currencies report published in October.
In it, bitcoin was described as "the most successful virtual currency", "which competes with the dollar or the euro" and "similar to conventional currencies".
Bitcoin differs from other systems with types of virtual currencies such as “credits”, used to advance in a video game and which can be earned by playing or purchased (and even sometimes exchanged).
The social network Facebook also developed this type of system.
But in every exchange a central authority controls and deals with changes.
With bitcoin, all network nodes are at the same time accounting book depositors, verificators, currency emitters and buyers and sellers.
How does that network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually made between two email addresses in the form of e-mail.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus guaranteeing anonymity.
A set of information linked to this transaction is signed electronically through a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the file content, it is also possible to ensure that bitcoins changes consist in the public account book, which is spread throughout the network.
The key thing is to write that new transaction in that book.
This passes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge launched to the computers and the winner, a kind of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
This is a phase of file-tracking, i.e. transforming a large file into a shorter and unique numerical footprint.
Computers “cogen” the new transaction and add a number before “treating” the set.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular footprint (more zero at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the good.
The transaction is then indestructively linked to the set chain of the other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, to commit a fraud, a user would like to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept as valid one of the two transactions; the other would be orphan, since both have different footprints.
The computer that solves the challenge takes 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, that reward is divided into two regularly, with probability before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is, therefore, limited to 21 million, but are divisible to the hundred million, leaving a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in every increase in the power of calculation.
The network has its heights.
Websites that offer services for Bitcoin have been attacked and Bitcoin deposits have been stolen.
“The fault used does not affect the same protocol,” says Pierre Noizat, who just launched Paymium, a real-money payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also takes into account the possibilities of money laundering thanks to this anonymous service.
