Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, from the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the accounting book and showed that about 80% of bitcoin is not circulating.
In November, the “gigant rebounds” were launched.
“They changed $30,000,” rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which turns bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, author of a pedagogical book about that currency, believes quite in the potential of this technology in addition to the network of transactions.
Your system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a contactless mobile payment, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which thus get cheaper.
The carrier also manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system is easy to launch in the stores, which do not have to install new terminals or software.
It is enough to provide an address that a phone can “photograph and recognize,” says Pierre Noizat, who assures to have thousands of users.
