A Constitution with Forceps in Egypt
This is a new double or nothing of President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever in terms of the constitutional declaration, which provisionally gives him full powers, he decided to play the whole for the whole.
He caught everyone by surprise on Wednesday, when he announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had given the Assembly two more months to finish his work.
And almost two years ago Egypt uses a provisional text, several times modified, which weakens institutional stability and leads to judicial embryo.
This new initiative has done nothing more than increasing the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the president persists in his "autocratic delirium" and continues to "trace his word" and "pisote the right".
Its supporters say it is a measure to finish the institutional and political crisis faster and accelerate the transition process.
A referendum should be held in the next 15 days.
A very short period of time that obliges the Brothers to give up their project of explaining the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way to recover a popular and democratic legitimacy while the controversy causes ruins throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote for him, as he said in an interview with the American weekly newspaper Time.
Considering that that resource has been voted very quickly, it contains an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "or they vote my text or I keep the full powers," powers that will supposedly end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in that strange environment in which 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, Islamist in its great majority, voted the text yesterday.
The majority of the liberals did not attend the call.
In mid-November, a little before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they thought they couldn’t make their points of view valid.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society did the same.
In order to the necessary quorum, 11 people, replacement members, were added yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brothers.
As expected, the articles voted unanimously.
The commentators are grateful, on the other hand, the fact that one of the few discrepancies of the day has been expressed practically at the time of prayer, so that several members of the committee came to think that the Constituent’s clock was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted yesterday afternoon, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, subject to all considerations, remains finally identical to that of the Constitution of 1971, which stipulated that “the principles of Sharia constitute the main source of law.”
The salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental claim, hoped that "principles" could be replaced by "norms", which would have allowed a more strict application.
For Islamists, that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their goodwill and their respect for the other components of the Egyptian society.
Liberalists tact it of hypocrisy and consider it not more than a advertising artifacts.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
It refers, in particular, to Article 220, which confers to the University of Al-Azhar a consultative role, in particular for anyone who has to confirm its compliance with the laws of the Sharia.
According to Egyptian expert Sophie Pommier, it’s annoying because “the people called to speak are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we see the premises of a theocracy.”
The fears of the liberals are also increased by the fact that the next rector of that university would be quite less moderate than the current.
For now, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution we are within the framework of the civil state.
The majority of the lawyers who have worked on that text are not ulemas but university students, some of them formed in the French system," explains Alexis Blouet, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But it acknowledges that there may be some ambiguity around article 220, since the terms used imitate the religious vocabulary.
“We refer in particular to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And the question that could be raised in the future would be in what extent the civil judges are competent to judge above all this.”
Beyond its religious character, the text voted yesterday has received many criticisms referring to the extended powers it confers to the President of the Republic.
Muslim Brothers will claim that they are few compared to those they were during the previous regime.
Another conflict: the powers conferred to the army.
According to the desire of the military, the revision of the defense budget will not be submitted to the Parliament, but to a national defense council.
Neither will civilians be prosecuted in military courts, as human rights defence associations demanded.
These also showed their concerns regarding the text, which they consider liberticid.
The crime of blasphemy remains and, from now on, insults are prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially the freedom of the press.
Moreover, no article emphasizes the protection of women, says Heba Morayef, from Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive thing was the prohibition of torture in accordance with Article 36.
The word was not included in the previous Constitution.
