What can this project actually contribute?What do you think are the conclusions?
Exactly a common control of this kind could help us stop investing efforts in the concretization of the laws, reducing and improving the limits, although this does not have such a positive impact.
Saving economy means getting a good thing at a reasonable price (which does not always mean that the price is the lowest) to avoid enrichment and, in the long run, criminal actions.
But not because of the fact that reducing the limit of the tender means that we’re going to get it.
Per because the system is saturated with so much "papeleo", that those who want to look for failures in the system will be able to do it easier than if the limits remain as high as now.
You talk about the problems of our country with the transfer of the legislation that regulates the practice of public procurement.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is it an office similar to our NKÚ or is it organized in a different way?
In how many offices, such as the NKÚ, there works the Bundesrechnungshof (Federal Court of Accounts), with an organization similar to our, with a college too, the only thing is that in your case it is structured in a slightly different way, but in principle both offices evolve parallelly.
Competences are also to a certain extent analogue, however, as long as Germany has a federal organization, accounting courts are even at this level.
The Federal Court of Accounts (BRH) can only control federal money, which here we call state funds.
Public funds, which are administered by the regions and municipalities there, in Germany, are controlled at the Federal Court of Accounts.
What about local law, is it simpler than our?
However, Germany remains a model in some aspects, but it cannot be accurately specified in what is better.
Could it be better, for example, as regards the quality of the inspectors?
That’s sure not, but, I repeat, I don’t like doing this kind of comparisons.
It is necessary to say that even those countries we take as a model should face a large number of problems.
If not so, they’t have any benefit from collaborating with our office, don’t you think?
As for the legislation of our country, what did the amendment to the law on public procurement mean for your Office?
Given that the validity period of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been manifested in the control actions.
Since we do ex post checks, it is necessary to have a certain delay.
For now, it is observed in the process of preparation of future controls: we have launched a new "non-economic risk detection" tool, by which we have passed 14,000 public procurements, which have been analyzed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, as the limits are modified, the conditions of some types of selection process and similar are rectified.
Do you think that the approval of this law is beneficial or that, rather, it implies an embryo for the bureaucratic system?
I think this law is a step in the right direction and I hope that it will be so.
The problem that may arise is that the regulation "weighs" and it is impossible to comply with it.
With the previous regulations, the controlled persons were linked to the contractor (for example, in the case of the regional operational programs of the regional council), and every law not respected in the field of public procurement meant the breach of the budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense to strengthen the law in this way?
I think not in this way.
The system must exclude those who want to attack it or take advantage of it and not punish those who commit a formal failure, which has no impact on decision making.
A system of this kind will only be able to create greater bureaucratic pressure.
How do you get out of this?
We will see where this path begins.
The prime minister has recently stated that the ODS would not bother entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called švarc system, with reference to the fact of being autonomous only on paper.
Is the shvarc system prohibited or permitted?
The law must be regulated in some way and, if it prohibits something, then not even the Prime Minister of the Government can prevent the Office's action that has the obligation to carry out such controls and require obligations.
You can say, "We change the law and allow it," but you can't say we'll do as if nothing.
In the law on public procurement, the regulations are quite strict as to the way it should act formally.
But, on the other hand, it is tragic that the candidate with the best offer is excluded because it does not meet the formal requirements.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct. This is, in my opinion, what we lack.
