Poland and the cosmos.
At the Ministers Meeting of the European Space Agency countries held last week, Poland was accepted as the twelfth member of the ESA. It is the second member of the ESA of the former block of Eastern Europe, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on November 12, 2008).
Poland began an intense collaboration with ESA in the year 1994 and during the subsequent years participated in the Agency’s project committee.
However, the path of Poland to the cosmos began much earlier.
The Polish enthusiasts were already dedicated to space flights before World War II, although their work was not always understood.
I remember, for example, A. Šternfeld’s conference at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory in which, on December 6, 1933, he presented his ideas on the pioneering study “Introduction to cosmonatics.”
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the assistants indifferent and, years later, Šternfeld remembered that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld was awarded in France the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize for their "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a great driver of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a series of books dedicated to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, was known all over the world and his contribution to science was rewarded when his name was put to one of the craters of the hidden face of the moon.
In 1925 a dresin was built in Poland, which was to be supplied with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, it is unknown who was the author of the proposal and the displays of the project are not known either.
It is not clear whether the rocket was to be used for the start of the dresin or for its braking.
The information about this dresin is limited to the information collected in the press of the time.
From 1933 the Polish artillery began to dedicate itself to the missiles.
The research was funded by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and Prof. Gustawem Mokrzyckiegim.
From the preserved material, it is clear that the research has reached the stage of practical tests.
However, with the arrival of the German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In 1937 the prototype of a photoelectric hunting missile designed by engineer Rohoziński appeared in the specialized press and the following year the study "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" was published by author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki.
Both projects were intended for military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was responsible for all missile techniques for military use projects and coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the beginning of the war.
Other studies dedicated to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Astronomical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
In the November 1954 edition of the magazine Problemy is referred for the first time to society with four very extensive articles dedicated to astronomy.
In one of them, of Prof. M. Subotowicze, it was proposed the creation of a society that would be devoted to cosmonautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was obvious that cosmic research was a discipline with future prospects.
Since the beginning of 1956 the Polish Astronomical Society (PTA) aspired to be part of the International Astronomical Federation (founded in 1951) and in the autumn of that same year the PTA became a full member.
The following year the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became the vice president of the International Federation of Astronomy.
He served this position until his death in 1959.
From 1956, the PTA participated significantly in the development of the RM (Meteorologiczna) missile, which was a success and became the first Polish missile in which scientific research was carried out.
The first RM-1 type was completed in 1957 and was first launched on 10 October 1958.
The rocket had a height of 1,800 meters, about 80 cm long and did not reach the 5 kg of weight.
Later, the RM-1A version was completed and in the summer of 1959 the two-stage RM-2 rocket air tests began in the Błędów desert.
The rocket was 1.4 meters and weighed about 11.5 kg.
The RM-34 rocket would have a peak of 14.5 km and its mission would be to control the wind of height.
However, in 1962 the work was suspended.
The successor of the first RM rocket was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during the years 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32,5 kg.
Three types were developed (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differentiated each other by the available space for scientific apparatus.
In the Meteor-1A rocket the available space for the volume was 0.4 liters, in the Meteor-1B of 0.34 liters and in the Meteor-1C of 0.62 liters.
The maximum peak in the three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968 the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Aerospace Institute, whose first air tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a useful weight of 10 kg up to 60 km of height.
The new version is Meteor-2H and Meteor-3.
It is also necessary to mention Poland's entry into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in the year 1960 and the formation of the COSPAR National Committee two years later.
In the framework of the Intercosmos program, Poland joined the cosmic space research on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
The suspension of the law on social work is not the solution.
Last week the Constitutional Court suspended the social labour law.
The resolution triggered a warming discussion in society.
Of course it will be interesting to look at the existing problem from a broader point of view.
Liberal economic systems in the EU, like in the globalized world, are based on the principle of greater economic competition and less regulatory.
Consequently, this means that the different economic forms and national economic systems are in permanent conflict with each other.
The cause lies in the principle of free trade and the free and unlimited movement of private capital, along with untouched financial speculation.
The effect of large differences in labour costs (the wages) produces economic tensions.
Under this concept it is necessary to understand the situation in which the manufacturer, with the import of cheap goods, tries to shorten distances and for this "prove a drop" of the competitor's price with the aim of doing with the majority of the market and, thus, increasing its profit margin.
On a large scale, it means, for most entrepreneurs, to move production abroad, buy there cheaper or either disappear. The result is a high unemployment in those countries where the price of labour, compared to other economies, is higher.
Because private capital has no social responsibility and, therefore, is not responsible for the unemployment that this phenomenon generates, the social expenditure of the state necessarily grows.
All this situation provokes the total disinterest of entrepreneurs for paying taxes and compensating the economic and social damage they have caused in their desire to obtain profits.
The situation is universally so known that it is not necessary to submit concrete statistical data.
The scrupulous practices of private capital create situations, in certain economies, in which governments of those countries are forced to compete with the aim of artificially reducing the social level of the population itself and thus attracting foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments put private capital at the disposal of their own population without taking into account the social decline.
This is evident in the changes in current laws.
The goal is to force the population to accept the dictates of private capital, especially in terms of wages.
This occurs, on the one hand, through the system of economic obligation in the case of long-term unemployment; on the other hand, through the employee’s restricted right as regards labour rights.
The result is a growing poverty along with the increased differences between poor and rich.
For a number of years, there have been food delivery points in Germany for poor people who cannot maintain themselves with their own work.
The number of people who receive this kind of aid reaches the million.
In the framework of the increased competitiveness of the German economy, a fairly frequent case occurs: people employed with a salary so low that the state must pay the rest to reach the minimum essential to survive.
A scandal of this kind was made public in connection with the situation of the auxiliary employees of the German federal parliament.
People, pressed by an abysmal decline of their social level, are forced to emigrate as in the nineteenth century or to disappear with a bad salary at the border of society, with the hope that one day it will reach the country capital private investor.
Is it necessary to wonder where it comes from?
If it comes to other EU countries, then poverty passes from one country to another or never comes, since Chinese, Indians, Brazilians, Turks, Moroccan, Egyptians or Africans continue to work for an infime part of a European salary.
This also affects Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media affirm to the satiety that the state should not bring capital to the economy, that directing the economy leads to its failure.
The private capital defends with nails and teeth the thesis that the state should not interfere in the economy by breaking into control.
Then it is necessary to wonder if private capital does not influence with its egoism on the political march and, therefore, throughout the state.
In this case, the answer is clearly yes.
The proof is the existence of lobbies, in practice very powerful and omnipresent, in all states.
The result is a desperate situation that manifests itself in the field of corruption, in mutual favors, in a legislation that is practically reprobable everywhere but is not punishable.
In Germany, the situation is as follows: the state ministries, in the lack of financial means, commission the drafting of law projects to private legal companies, which are often linked to the industry.
This type of bills are later approved in the Bundestag, the German parliament.
Thus, all power does not emerge from the people, as it is proclaimed in the constitutions of Western democracies, but from the strong financial groups that represent their own interests.
