The conclusion, as in ancient times, is that today’s society is based on discontinued preferences of individual benefit without taking into account the common interests.
The private capital is unable, in its essence, to understand and claim the benefits of the whole society.
The result is the same as that of then, an unprecedented decadence of the elite, without an effort to reform it in depth.
The causes of the rise of fascist and communist regimes must therefore be sought in the unfinished liberalization of economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
