But the release of the prisoners in Iran, where the revolution had led to the constitution of the theocratic regime, was not at its reach.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which later intensified even more with the failed attempt to release the prisoners by force.
The prisoners were released 444 days after the Algerian government’s negotiating intervention.
In the U.S., his fate caused a wave of solidarity and animation against Iran.
The failure in Iran contributed decisively to the defeat of Jimmy Carter against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film "Argo" by director and actor Ben Affleck theme an episode of this story, which harvested a small success for America.
Shortly before occupying the embassy, six employees escaped from the building.
After a complicated periple, they ended in the residence of the Canadian Embassy.
CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, for this helped a hidden story an extravagant point: they went out with Canadian passports, as members of the film team that examined the location in the country for the recording of a science fiction superproduction.
Combination of gender
The plan drawn by the "exfiltration" expert Toni Mendez required Hollywood's collaboration.
So that the lie seemed true, it was written about the film project in specialized magazines, press conferences were organized, the fictional production society had even a real office.
The details about the operation were kept in secret for a long time, the film has been made from the memories of Tony Mendez.
The Affleck film is a unique combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a realistic political thriller; on the other hand, a so-called "caper movie", the story of an episode that came out well, a deception (a example may be the Ocean's Eleven series).
We find on the one hand well-documented sequences of Tehran. In the credit sequence are displayed emblematic photographs of the time of events, which were shaped in the same way in the film; there are not many differences in this regard.
On the other hand, typical Hollywood scenes are slightly lighter, marked by irony and a slight exaggeration.
And in addition, scenes from the CIA and other institutions: dressed men who analyze the situation at the negotiation table, in the halls of the office, by telephone...
Ben Affleck has managed to reboot his career in an excellent way.
The actor, who had been the subject of joke, has become a respectful director and his way of acting has ceased to be the white of ironic comments.
Argo is his third long-movie, after "Goodbye Little, Goodbye" (2007) and the thriller "The Town: City of Thieves" (2010).
At the same time, it’s Affleck’s first film in which the action does not take place in the city of Boston, where he grew up.
Also, the sensitivity of capturing the atmosphere of the place was a feature that placed the directors of ancient films above Hollywood standards.
And Affleck demonstrates it in Argo, where Tehran “routes” in Canada.
The introductory sequence of the embassy is impressive for its synoptic capacity that, at the same time, transmits the emotion of disconcert and lack of forecast that arises when, somewhere, the story gives a step forward.
Affleck and his collaborators get a similar effect on fictional scenes (the impostor team at the Tehran bazar).
Too much action in too many places
The director had to accept the fact that an explained story does not offer much in the cinematographic sense of the most intriguing scenes.
Sometimes it adds something to reality: here it doesn’t come out all so elegantly (the scene in which the crisis at the Tehran airport, the deviation of a call to America and the unfinished search for its track become a madness).
The weakness of Argo is the incontrol that arises from the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman have a very funny role as Hollywood collaborators, although their characters deserved more space and are not, much less, the only ones in this film.
For these reasons, Affleck's film loses a little dramatic trace, but it's a film that can be followed with a moderate interest, valuing its realization and the retro style of a thriller that evokes the 1970s.
But if it collapses, it will be difficult.
As an evocation of a real story and as proof of how exaggerated the notions of omnipresence and omniscience of the secret services can be, it is enough.
