And so was the way the political leaders decided that there was only one possibility to improve the statistics: it had to build a library!
Winy Maas, from the Dutch architecture studio MVRDV, all a master in the art of bar diagrams and responsible for fun and cynical buildings, took the topic with his usual serenity and compared to the presentation of the contest in the year 2003 with five books under the arm and a smile on the face.
And while the jury looked confused around him and shrinked on his shoulders, Maas went to shrink the books by size forming a pyramid and concluded his brief speech with the following words: "Dear citizens:
Here you have it, my proposal for Spijkenisse’s book mountain, the so-called ‘Boekenberg’.
Nine years later, the mountain of 30 million euros rises in the planned place.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is completed with a underground parking, a supermarket, a postal office and a couple of housing and housing buildings.
In early November, the book mountain was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project is also nominated for the "Dutch National Wood Award 2012".
In this way, the little city lacking in history, which so far had nothing more than to offer than a postmodern pedestrian area and an incredibly ugly municipality behind whose white façade one would intuit rather a milk center, now has a work of contemporary architecture.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The long way to the book
The first impression is that it is a book paradise under a quesera.
It’s true that there’s an elevator that carries us right in the center of this mountainous mass, but true space and reading lovers don’t use it, but they prefer to fuse with their topography at every step of their climbing to the top.
The completely crystaled interior is bright and easy to cover with the view, the ground of brick and the elegant lamps unquestionably support the public condition of the library.
The urban environment is perfect.
By raising the view, you can get to visualize the banks of the park, dogs and boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
“Normally the book shelves are placed along the façade and in the center an enormous dark room opens which is usually somewhat uncomfortable and impersonal,” says Winy Maas.
What we have done is to put up the classic space configuration and get the reading area from the interior to the outside.
The mountain interior is very well exploited: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education center and the maintenance room.
Special mention deserves the black roofs that assume the functions of wall coating, parapet and barrel at the same time.
The sight, touch and smell are strange.
Even architects and civil engineers more daily shake their heads when they hear about this unknown material.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” explains Joop Trouborst, project chief in the city of Spijkenisse.
And that’s how one day, in a fresh farm, we meet with the adequate subproduct from agriculture.
For many years, in the greenhouses and fields of the Netherlands, a small-millimeter thick plastic tissue has been used as a base to subject the roots of the crops.
It is a cheap and efficient material.
This thin tissue lasts two seasons and then dissolves.
For the library this tissue was pressed, for the first time in such amounts, until it achieved four-cm thick plates.
With heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes color and turns into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material that smells a mixture of new car and sports shoes.
After 105 hills it reaches the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous route of almost 500 meters around the mountain we are waiting for the reward: from the cafeteria not only you have a fantastic view of the city, but in it you can also enjoy some delicious Dutch croquettes and their ficus planted in enormous strawberries.
These create a pleasant atmosphere along withining the adequate atmospheric humidity for this mountain of literature.
Donations for a new soul
“While it’s hard to believe given its large crystal surfaces, this building is an exemplary project in terms of ecology,” says Trouborst.
The necessary heating and cooling are obtained from geothermal energy.
Although the book mountain is located under an enormous crystal pyramid, even in the sunny days the sun only shines for a few hours in its interior.
The enormous wooden shores located in transversal direction to the crystal façade serve to give shadow and absorb most of the sun's rays.
This creates a comfortable interior climate.
The rest is about automatic persian.
