The access of journalists to the summit information was restricted at all times.
During the day, in the press room, the presidential assembly's soundless video with the message "private session, restricted audio" was only transmitted.
The little information that circulated among the reporters was delivered by the press spokesmen of some of the Unasur governments attending the date, although not the Peruvian.
The only document released during the day was the list of assistant presidents, which caused the discomfort of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for greater data.
Later, the Presidency of Peru sent an email to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it is the pronunciation of Humala, and not the official document that closed the summit.
Last October, Peru was the host of the Third Summit of South American Arab Countries (ASPA), and on that occasion, despite being insistently requested by the press, the so-called Declaration of Lima that previously had been announced was not spread.
The official website of ASPA can be confirmed that the document was published last Tuesday.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities strived to ensure that there were secure broadcast systems for all journalists but limited to the maximum the obtaining of information.
The summit also concluded with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to accept a court ruling that directs a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and ratified that they will respect the decision of the (CIJ), which begins Monday in The Hague to hear the allegations of both parties, in the process that Lima presented against Santiago.
"We will catch and execute the sentence that defines the differences that we are bringing to this international court today," Humala said, along with his Chilean couple.
“Chile has been, is and will continue to be a country that respects international law, the peaceful settlement of disputes, treaties and international courts,” Piñera added, and greeted Humala, alongside the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation of both presidents that they will submit to the CIJ occurred after Colombia denounced this week the Bogotá Pact by which it had accepted to submit to the failures of that international court, after a decision on maritime boundaries with Nicaragua which it considered seriously wrong.
The summit was held with the inassistences of the Brazilian presidents, Dilma Rouseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chávez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the dismissal of his former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
