With Europe in crisis, “economic consolidation (from Latin America) should not have a triumphal matrix but should serve to expand productive matrix and see a better future for our peoples,” Humala added.
"We have decided to privilege a group of 31 emblematic projects that will improve the connection of the spaces of South America, especially in rural and border areas ... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits," the Peruvian president said in a read message.
Among those projects, he mentioned that five correspond to Peru, and are located in the transversal axis of their territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two point to a greater connection with Ecuador, although he did not give greater details.
The final document also mentioned the political situation in Paraguay.
“We hope that the electoral process in that country will serve for its reincorporation to the Union of South American Nations,” from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated, and of good relations between neighbors, was another of the issues highlighted by the summit.
In this sense, the president of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before starting his participation in the regional meeting he hoped to meet with his Nicaragua couple, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico to treat in respect the maritime dispute after a CIJ decision, questioned by Bogotá.
