Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to give a course on the end of the world, he knew that he had an irresistible anthem: the end of the "long regressive account" of the Maya Calendar, on December 21, to which many people have attached as a proof that the end of the world is coming.
But Charmé had no idea what was waiting for him in the next couple of months: the cataclysmic hurricane Sandy, a tax precipient that some have called "deudarmagedon" and a growing conflict that involves Israel, the place where the Christian theorists of the end of the times believe that the Apocalypse will begin.
"I didn't realize that this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester ever," Charmé said this week to students at Rutgers-Camden University (New Jersey).
